Fig. 2 (a) shows the X-ray diffraction (XRD) patterns of the CuO and CuO:Co samples. In the XRD patterns of both samples, the major diffraction peaks at 2θ = 32.5, 35.5, 38.7, 48.7, 53.4, 58.2, 61.5, 66.2 and 68.1° were well indexed to the corresponding (110), (11
1 ¯
), (111), (20
2 ¯
), (020) (202) (11
3 ¯
) (311) and (220) planes, respectively and the results are in good agreement with monoclinic CuO phase (JCPDS card # 48–1548) with a space group of C2/c (15). Furthermore, it is noted that the CuO:Co sample displayed a major diffraction peak at 2θ = 36.5 with the hexagonal CoO crystal structure having (101) crystal plane (JCPDS card # 89–2803). To find the functional groups in the synthesized samples, FTIR analysis was carried out as shown in Fig. 2(b). The FTIR spectra of the CuO and CuO:Co samples were measured in the wavenumber range of 4000 to 450 cm−1. The vibrational modes of the CuO samples were observed in the wavenumber range of 500–700 cm−1. The infrared absorption bands at 512 and 600 cm−1 are related to the Cu-O stretching vibrational modes [36]. The bands at 1404 and 1546 cm−1 are corresponding to the C-H vibrational bands of the HMTA surfactant. The broad absorption band at approximately 3349 cm−1 indicates the presence of O-H stretching bands of the water molecules during the crystallinity of the CuO and CuO:Co samples [37].
